title: For Sale:  US Springfield M1892/96 Krag Rifle
postcontent:
Original condition M1892 Krag Rifle, US issue during the Spanish American War and Philippine Insurrection.
I have owned this rifle for over 20 years, and it came out of another long-term collection when I purchased it. It is unmessed with.
Per several sources, based on the serial number of 9475, this one was initially manufactured as a M1892 around 1895 and at some point soon thereafter recalled and altered to the M1896 configuration, as most of the M1892’s were.
There are no other modifications or alterations.
It retains the original wood finish and reddish brown Springfield Arsenal color. While the wood is sound, it clearly shows signs of use.
The original Inspector’s cartouche is gone, probably a function of the period alteration. The ‘circle P’ proof is present on the underside of the stock, rear of the triggerguard.
On the top of the comb, near the buttplate, is stamped (I think) “121”. That’s probably a rack number.
On the right side of the buttstock, near the buttplate is stamped “WI”. I would speculate that this indicates a Wisconsin connection.
The barrel blue is good, thinning at the muzzle.
I see no pitting.
Marked ‘1894 Springfield Armory 9475’ on the receiver.
No reblue or stock alterations.
Included with the rifle:
1.Original M1887 leather sling. Surface cracking evident. Still very flexible.
2.Original brass front sight / muzzle cover.
3.Complete set of cleaning rods and nickel-plated oiler.
Think about this for a minute; this rifle is coming with over $300 worth of very hard to find accoutrements. It’s a complete package and you don’t need to hunt for a year to find these rare accessories.
Many more photos (35 presently) can be seen here:
http://s214.photobucket.com/user/R_S_Hubbard/li brary/Krag%20M1892_96
Note the photo of the bore/action/chamber show what looks like rust; it’s not – just preservative grease. It’s very clean.
Questions are welcome; PLEASE ask if you have any.
